er 1410":"29 november 1410","1374":"1374","1451":"1451","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","8 September 1358":"8 september 1358","1359":"1359","1325":"1325","1413":"1413","1358":"1358","1410":"1410","1355":"1355","6 August 1375":"6 augustus 1375","1387":"1387","1343":"1343","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","1386":"1386","about 1386":"circa 1386","Bobbing, Swale Borough, Kent, England":"Bobbing, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Of, Bobbing Court, Kent, England":"Bobbing, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bobbing, Kent, England":"Bobbing, Kent, England"},"en":{"8 September 1358–29 November 1410":"8 September 1358–29 November 1410","1355–Female":"1355–Deceased","1358–1410":"1358–1410","1359–1413":"1359–1413","1383–1420":"1383–1420","1386–1451":"1386–1451","1387–1451":"1387–1451","1325–1374":"1325–1374","1343–1375":"1343–1375","29 November 1410":"29 November 1410","1374":"1374","1451":"1451","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","8 September 1358":"8 September 1358","1359":"1359","1325":"1325","1413":"1413","1358":"1358","1410":"1410","1355":"1355","6 August 1375":"6 August 1375","1387":"1387","1343":"1343","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","1386":"1386","about 1386":"about 1386","Bobbing, Swale Borough, Kent, England":"Bobbing, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Of, Bobbing Court, Kent, England":"Bobbing, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Bobbing, Kent, England":"Bobbing, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Savage","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a nickname for a wild or uncouth person, from Middle English and Old French <i>salvage</i>, <i>sauvage</i> ‘wild, untamed’ (from Late Latin <i>salvaticus</i>, literally ‘man of the woods’, a derivative of Latin <i>silva</i> ‘wood’ influenced by Latin <i>salvus</i> ‘whole’, i.e. natural). Compare French   Sauvage  .","Irish (Down): generally of English origin (it was taken to County Down in the 12th century), this name has also sometimes been adopted as equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó Sabháin</b>, the name of a small south Munster sept, which was earlier Anglicized as <b>O'Savin</b> (see   Savin  ).","Americanized form of Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Savich   and of Serbian <b>Savić</b> (see   Savic  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Savitt","meanings":["Possibly English or Irish: variant of   Savage  . This surname is very rare in Britain.","Alternatively, perhaps an Americanized form of Jewish   Savich   or an American shortened and altered form of Jewish   Savitski  ."]},{"name":"Sauvage","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Michel, Armand, Jean-Jacques.","French and Channel Islands: nickname for a wild or uncouth person, from Old French <i>salvage</i>, <i>sauvage</i> ‘untamed’ (from Late Latin <i>salvaticus</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>silva</i> ‘wood’, influenced by Latin <i>salvus</i> ‘whole’, i.e. natural). This surname is also found in England.","History: Jean Sauvage from Plouëc-du-Trieux in Côtes-d'Armor, Brittany (France), married Marguerite Martin in Les Cèdres, QC, in 1782."]},{"name":"Salvage","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Monique.","English (Sussex): variant of   Savage  .","Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish surname."]},{"name":"Ramage","meanings":["Scottish and English (of Norman origin); French: nickname for a savage or unpredictable individual, from Old French <i>ramage</i> ‘wild, untamed’. The word is recorded once in Middle English with the sense ‘courageous’ and in Scots (spelled <i>rammage</i>) as ‘rash, furious’. Compare   Savage  ."]},{"name":"Sabin","meanings":["English (Warwickshire and Northamptonshire): from the Middle English personal name <i>Sabin</i> (from Latin <i>Sabinus</i>; see 2 below) or its female equivalent <i>Sabine</i> (from Latin <i>Sabina</i>). In medieval England the feminine form was always more popular as a personal name.","French: from the Old French personal name <i>Sabin</i>, from Latin <i>Sabinus</i>. The name was originally referred to the Sabines, an ancient Italic people of central Italy whose name is of uncertain origin. In the 8th century  BC  the Romans slaughtered the Sabine menfolk and carried off the women. More influential as far as name-giving is concerned was the existence of several early Christian saints named <i>Sabinus</i>.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Sabháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Sabhán</i>’, a personal name based on <i>sabh</i> ‘cub’. As an Irish surname, this has mostly been absorbed into   Savage  ."]},{"name":"Selvidge","meanings":["English (Leicestershire):","from Middle English <i>selvage</i>, <i>silvadge</i> ‘edge of a cloth, bandage, ornamental edging (to a cloth or garment)’, hence a nickname for someone who made or sold such items.","variant of   Savage  ."]},{"name":"Savidge","meanings":["English: variant of   Savage  ."]}]},{"name":"Arnold","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  Jewish: Yiddish contracted form of   Aaron .","2  English: short form of   Arnold ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":23,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Arnold Savage II was born on 8 September 1358, in Bobbing, Kent, England, his father, Arnold Savage, was 34 and his mother, Eleanor St. Leger, was 16. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Joan Echyngham. He died on 29 November 1410, in his hometown, at the age of 52, and was buried in Bobbing, Kent, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"8 September 1358–29 November 1410":"8. s